Problem set 2: NHANES

1/17/2018

Heights

# install.packages("NHANES")
library(NHANES)
# Subset the adults:
Adults = subset(NHANES, Age >= 18)
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(Adults, aes(x = Height, group = Gender, color = Gender)) + geom_density()
## Warning: Removed 57 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Women = subset(Adults, Gender == "female")
Men = subset(Adults, Gender == "male")
women.heights = Women$Height
men.heights = Men$Height
summary(women.heights)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   134.5   157.2   162.1   162.1   167.1   184.5      29
summary(men.heights)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   149.4   171.0   175.7   175.9   180.7   200.4      28
sd(women.heights, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 7.27444
sd(men.heights, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 7.482339
qqplot(women.heights, men.heights)
abline(mean(men.heights, na.rm = TRUE) - mean(women.heights, na.rm = TRUE), 1, col = "red")

summary(log(women.heights))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   4.902   5.058   5.088   5.087   5.119   5.218      29
summary(log(men.heights))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   5.007   5.142   5.169   5.169   5.197   5.300      28
sd(log(women.heights), na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.04503751
sd(log(men.heights), na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.04261887
qqplot(log(women.heights), log(men.heights))
abline(mean(log(men.heights), na.rm = TRUE) - mean(log(women.heights), na.rm = TRUE), 1, col = "red")

An additive shift seems sufficient to describe the difference. The distributions of heights of women and men are similar, except that men are, on average, about 14 cm taller than women.

Neither an additive nor a multiplicative shift seems sufficient to describe the difference, though if we had to choose, the additive shift looks a bit better. An additive shift of about 14 kg works well for the bulk of the distributions, but breaks down at the top end (though it’s hard to be sure about the distributions in the upper tail because of lack of data.)

Residual-fit plot

# Fit a model
height.lm = lm(Height ~ Gender, data = Adults)
Fitted = fitted.values(height.lm) - mean(fitted.values(height.lm))
Residuals = residuals(height.lm)
# Create a data frame with the results
height.fit = data.frame(Fitted, Residuals)
# Gather into long form
library(tidyr)
height.fit.log = gather(height.fit, key=type, value=value, Fitted:Residuals)
ggplot(height.fit.log, aes(sample=value)) + stat_qq(distribution=qunif) + facet_grid(~type) + xlab("Quantiles of the standard uniform distribution") + ylab("Values from the model (cm)") + ggtitle("Residual-fit spread plot for model predicting height from gender")

# R^2
var(Fitted) / (var(Fitted) + var(Residuals))
## [1] 0.4671213
